    "faq_section_RX9irX": {
      "type": "faq-section",
      "blocks": {
        "faq_item_fRAbQd": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "Why does my engagement ring look dull in photos?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>Your ring may look dull because lighting, residue, or shadows can block the sparkle. Harsh light creates glare, while dim light makes the diamond look flat. Fingerprints, lotions, and dust also reduce shine. Clean the ring gently, use soft daylight near a window, and tilt your hand slowly until you see the diamond catch light. Small adjustments in angle and lighting often bring back the brilliance in engagement ring photos.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_MWMJyb": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "How to prevent diamonds from getting cloudy?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>Diamonds look cloudy when oils, dirt, or product buildup collect around the facets. To prevent this, clean your ring regularly using warm water and mild soap. Avoid letting lotions, perfume, and hair products touch the diamond. Remove the ring during workouts or household tasks that can create residue. A gentle weekly cleaning at home and an occasional professional polish will keep the stone bright, clear, and camera ready.</p>"
          }
        },
        "faq_item_mTAJhw": {
          "type": "faq_item",
          "settings": {
            "faq_question": "How to make diamonds shine more on camera?",
            "faq_answer": "<p>To capture the natural shine, clean your ring before every photo so no residue blocks the light. Use soft natural lighting, like sunlight through a window, which brings out clarity and sparkle. Hold your hand loosely, avoid stiff poses, and tilt the diamond slightly toward the light source. Try different angles, use portrait mode when possible, and keep filters minimal so the diamond’s real brightness shows through in your pictures.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
